<subSubSection id="449F10A9D39A763EC578885B20CF2AFE" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="22C499CDD3525F014F76626894DF6499" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DA9645C38CF933646B389175554217BE" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Very similar vegetatively to 
<taxonomicName id="CBFAE9D2C7B100B9BD58386985B35410" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="suburceolata">
<emphasis id="8ABF4EBC2BD47FFDFAB61598622F39B9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea suburceolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but easily distinguished by the funnel-shaped corolla with a well-developed entire limb. It has often been misidentified as 
<taxonomicName id="25AE270E7DE8ADC3FBB4B025A9D3DF58" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="batatoides">
<emphasis id="4F0E69B583942B8F8BBB402CAFC66064" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. batatoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differs in the leaf shape and inflorescence structure, the flowers often being borne on leafy side shoots.
</paragraph>
